# PART A — BRD Full Reference

*(Transcribed from `Pharma_BRD_V0_1.pdf`)*

## A.1 Business Objective (BRD §1)

The primary business objective is to enable efficient, compliant, and scalable execution of clinical trials by replacing manual, fragmented trial operations with a deterministic, rules-driven Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS) that actively manages clinical workflows rather than passively recording data.

Specifically, the solution aims to:

- **Reduce operational inefficiency and errors** by automating study, site, subject, visit, document, task, and financial workflows through configuration-based, deterministic rules.
- **Increase real-time visibility and control** over trial progress, risks, and compliance status across studies, sites, and regions using a centralized single source of truth.
- **Ensure regulatory compliance and inspection readiness by design**, with complete audit trails, traceability, controlled access, and explainable system behavior.
- **Lower validation and maintenance cost** by avoiding opaque AI-driven logic and focusing on transparent, predictable processes that are easy to validate and upgrade.
- **Improve scalability and adaptability** to protocol amendments, geographic expansion, and increasing operational complexity without requiring custom code.
- **Minimize administrative burden and reconciliation errors** by tightly integrating operational milestones with financial rules and payment controls.
- **Enhance patient engagement and retention** through a secure patient portal that supports self-management, timely communication, and reduced dependency on site staff.
- **Enable teams to focus on exception management and decision-making**, rather than routine tracking and manual coordination.

Overall, the objective is to run clinical trials more predictably, compliantly, and cost-effectively, accelerating study timelines while increasing confidence among sponsors, CROs, QA teams, and regulators.

## A.2 Background (BRD §2)

Clinical trial execution involves managing many interdependent processes across studies, sites, subjects, visits, documents, finances, and compliance. In many organizations, these activities are handled through manual and fragmented tools such as spreadsheets, emails, and disconnected systems, resulting in inefficiency, errors, and delays.

The lack of automation and integration makes real-time visibility into trial progress difficult, limiting proactive risk management and operational control. At the same time, clinical trials are highly compliance-sensitive, requiring complete audit trails, traceability, and controlled access — needs that manual systems struggle to meet consistently.

As trial complexity increases with more sites, geographies, and regulatory oversight, these approaches do not scale effectively. Although several CTMS platforms exist, many rely on complex AI-driven features that increase validation effort, maintenance cost, and system opacity, making them unsuitable for organizations that primarily need predictable, explainable, and rule-based process automation.

This creates a clear need for a CTMS that actively manages trial operations, improves transparency and compliance, and scales through deterministic, configuration-driven workflows rather than AI-based abstraction.

## A.3 Scope of the Clinical Trial Management Solution (BRD §3)

The scope of this solution covers the end-to-end operational execution of clinical trials, focusing on deterministic, rules-based automation across all core trial processes. It is designed to replace manual, fragmented workflows with a centralized, compliant, and configurable CTMS that actively manages trial activities.

### A.3.1 In Scope

- **Study & Site Management:** End-to-end lifecycle management including study setup, site activation, approvals, status transitions, and prerequisite enforcement.
- **Subject & Visit Management:** Protocol-driven subject enrollment, visit scheduling, visit tracking, and management of missed or overdue visits with version control.
- **Workflow & Task Automation:** Automated creation, assignment, tracking, and escalation of tasks based on system events, schedules, and SLA rules.
- **Monitoring & Oversight:** CRA assignment, monitoring visit planning, report tracking, follow-up actions, and automated milestone calculations (e.g., FPI, LPI, DBL).
- **Document & Compliance Management:** Controlled document storage, classification, versioning, approval workflows, and immutable audit trails for inspection readiness.
- **Financial Management:** Visit- and activity-based payment rules, compliance-linked payment releases, budget management, and protocol amendment alignment.
- **Reporting & Transparency:** Real-time dashboards, operational metrics across studies and portfolios, and exportable reports for internal review and regulatory inspections.
- **Patient Portal:** Secure patient access for visit visibility, task completion, reminders, document uploads (where permitted), and self-service updates.
- **Configuration & Validation:** Configuration-driven rules, workflows, and schedules with full traceability, enabling easier validation and regulatory acceptance.

### A.3.2 Out of Scope

- Advanced AI/ML-based predictive analytics or black-box decision-making.
- Clinical data analysis (EDC), safety systems, or lab data management **beyond operational linkage**.

Overall, the scope emphasizes running and enforcing clinical trial operations through transparent, scalable, and compliance-first automation rather than passive tracking or predictive intelligence.

