## Epic 11: Regulatory Compliance (GCP, 21 CFR Part 11, Audit Trail, Data Integrity)

### Story 01 – Enforce GCP (Good Clinical Practice) Compliance

**User Story:** As a Compliance Officer, I want the system to enforce GCP guidelines so that clinical trial processes meet international ethical and scientific quality standards.
**Detailed Description:** The system must ensure that documentation, monitoring activities, training records, data capture, and audit trails align with ICH-GCP standards. It should ensure all essential documents are present, informed consent is recorded properly, deviations are tracked, and workflows follow GCP-compliant sequences.
**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. System validates presence of required essential documents.
2. Informed consent must be uploaded before any subject activity.
3. Protocol deviations captured and logged.
4. Monitoring visits must follow GCP structure.
5. All actions captured in audit trail.
6. Role-based access aligned with GCP requirements.
**Size:** 8 (large) | **Priority:** High

### Story 02 – Ensure 21 CFR Part 11 Compliance (Electronic Records & Signatures)

**User Story:** As a Compliance Officer, I want full 21 CFR Part 11 compliance so that electronic records and signatures are legally valid, secure, and traceable.
**Detailed Description:** System must enforce identity verification, secure audit trails, restricted access, electronic signature timestamps, reason-for-signing, and validation of electronic records. Signed documents must be locked and protected. *[Implementation note: identity verification uses password re-authentication only — no MFA-backed signing. See Implementation Plan Open Items for the recommended QA/Compliance sign-off on this deviation.]*
**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. eSignatures require username, password, and reason for signing.
2. Signed records locked from editing.
3. Audit trail includes signature details (user, timestamp).
4. Access to sensitive documents restricted by roles.
5. System prevents signature repudiation.
**Size:** 8 (large) | **Priority:** High

### Story 03 – Maintain Data Integrity Following ALCOA Principles

**User Story:** As an Auditor, I want data integrity enforced using ALCOA principles so that clinical data remains reliable and audit-ready.
**Detailed Description:** The system must ensure all data is: **A**ttributable (captured with user identity), **L**egible (clearly readable), **C**ontemporaneous (timestamped at entry), **O**riginal (preserved in original form), **A**ccurate (validated and complete). Edits should require reasons and be fully versioned.
**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Every record has user identity, timestamp, and origin.
2. Edits trigger versioning and require reason codes.
3. System prevents deletion of original data.
4. All entries must pass validation rules.
5. Audit logs capture before/after values.
**Size:** 8 (large) | **Priority:** High

### Story 04 – Enable Full End-to-End Traceability

**User Story:** As an Auditor, I want full end-to-end traceability across the system so that every action, change, and record can be traced back for regulatory review.
**Detailed Description:** System must show complete traceability for every data element, including creation, modification, signatures, workflow changes, approvals, and user interactions. A single traceability report must be exportable for audits.
**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Traceability logs linked to every field and document.
2. Users can view change history including old/new values.
3. Exportable traceability reports available.
4. No edits allowed without audit entries.
5. Time-stamped and user-attributed logs maintained permanently.
**Size:** 8 (large) | **Priority:** High

**Epic IPO Notes:** *Inputs:* User actions (create/update/delete), electronic signatures, data updates, access logs. *Processing:* Capture audit logs, enforce ALCOA rules, apply 21 CFR Part 11 controls, validate data integrity. *Outputs:* Audit trail reports, eSignature records, compliance validation alerts, traceability logs, regulatory reports.

